;s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2015-04-28T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Robby\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Robby.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:72:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2015-04-28:/monitoring-and-service-discovery.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:787:\"<p>At Mandrill, API uptime is essential. We have to ensure all the pieces of our architecture are happy and healthy. When they\'re not, we need to take them away quickly and automagically so they don\'t negatively impact our users. We accomplish the automagic bits using some off-the-shelf tools and our own homegrown tooling we call \"Pulse.\"</p>\n\n<p>Configuration management has seen massive improvements recently. You can take your pick between any of the popular tools—Puppet, Chef, Ansible, Salt, my-custom-bash-script.sh, etc.—and all will get the job done, but one question that these tools haven\'t fully answered is the idea of service discovery. We needed some tooling to tie together deployment, configuration management, and service discovery. And thus, Pulse was born.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"