customers of a security vulnerability we discovered in Mandrill’s infrastructure. At this time, we’re confident that no customer data was compromised as a result of the vulnerability, but we feel it’s our responsibility to let our customers know exactly what happened and what we’re doing about it.</p>\n\n<p>Since this issue only applies to Mandrill accounts that were used between February 6 and March 10, we emailed everyone who may have been affected. If you didn’t get an email from us today, that means you weren’t affected. For other Mandrill users and affected users who choose to notify their own customers about the vulnerability, this post explains what happened.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"announcements\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"Handling Advanced Customer Behavior Triggers with Customer.io\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:91:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/handling-advanced-customer-behavior-triggers-with-customer-io.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2015-03-06T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Nathan\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Nathan.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:101:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2015-03-06:/handling-advanced-customer-behavior-triggers-with-customer-io.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:838:\"<p>As a Mandrill support analyst, I get a lot of questions from users looking for quick and easy ways to send triggered emails based on a customer’s interaction with their application or site. For example, they may want to send a series of onboarding emails to new customers to help them get the most out of important features by including tips, tricks, or tutorials. Our <a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/21738186-Introduction-to-Webhooks\">webhooks</a> are a powerful way to get the data needed to trigger these types of interaction-specific emails, but they’re only one piece of the puzzle. It’s still necessary to create the logic to handle those triggers, and that’s not always feasible for smaller teams or for those who don’t have the development resources to set up and maintain that kind of advanced logic.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:12:\"integrations\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"Handlebars for templates and dynamic content\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:74:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/handlebars-for-templates-and-dynamic-content.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2015-01-13T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Kaitlin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Kaitlin.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:84:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2015-01-13:/handlebars-for-templates-and-dynamic-content.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1151:\"<p>In November we quietly rolled out a new template language using <a href=\"http://handlebarsjs.com\">Handlebars</a> to support more complex dynamic content and templates. Since a full email strategy often involves different people&mdash;from developers to marketing to content editors (and more)&mdash;templates help separate data about an order, for example, from the formatting and style of the email. Handlebars gives your entire team more control and flexibility, including support for iterating over a collection (<a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/handlebars-for-templates-and-dynamic-content.html#loops\">loops</a>) and conditional data. </p>\n\n<p>If you want to start using Handlebars right away, check out our <a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/105267476-Using-Handlebars-for-dynamic-content\">documentation</a> to see what\'s supported, or <a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/handlebars-for-templates-and-dynamic-content.html#examples\">skip ahead to examples</a>. If you\'re interested in learning about why we added a new template language and our process for releasing it (including why we didn\'t announce it from the start), read on.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"release-notes\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:30:\"Updated SSL Certs for Mandrill\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:60:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/updated-ssl-certs-for-mandrill.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2014-12-08T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Kaitlin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Kaitlin.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2014-12-08:/updated-ssl-certs-for-mandrill.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1408:\"<p><strong><em>Update December 17, 2014, 4:55pm EST</strong>: As with most changes in Mandrill, we rolled this one out using a progressive migration from our smallest region to our largest region while monitoring server loads, error rates, and user feedback through support channels. While our initial estimation that a fraction of users would be impacted was correct, the severity of that impact in some cases was more greater than anticipated.</em></p>\n\n<p><em>The initial changes we made included updates to both our root certificate and intermediate certificate chain, so that everything used SHA-2. This resulted in errors, particularly for users in shared hosting environments where SHA-2 is supported, but the root cert bundles couldn\'t be updated in a timely fashion. We\'ve partially rolled back this change to a configuration with a SHA-1 root, and SHA-2 intermediate certificates, which should address the majority of issues users were reporting. We\'ll continue to monitor the status of this, and provide further updates if necessary.</em></p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p>Next <strong>Wednesday, December 17, 2014</strong>, we’re making some updates to Mandrill’s SSL certificates to ensure they’re no longer using SHA-1 hashing algorithms for signing. The change is anticipated to impact a very small number of users — those using an older server, and more specifically, an older SSL client library.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"announcements\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"POODLE SSLv3 Vulnerability\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:49:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/poodle-sslv3-update.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2014-10-16T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Dustin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Dustin.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2014-10-16:/poodle-sslv3-update.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1680:\"<p>Yesterday, <a href=\"http://googleonlinesecurity.blogspot.com/2014/10/this-poodle-bites-exploiting-ssl-30.html\">Google released information about POODLE, a serious vulnerability in SSL version 3.0</a>. This vulnerability can\'t be used to gain unauthorized access to the Mandrill infrastructure, but in theory a malicious network operator could use it to eavesdrop on encrypted communications. We\'re updating Mandrill\'s infrastructure to protect against this vulnerability by completely disabling support for the SSLv3 protocol.</p>\n\n<p>2014 brought the announcement of several high-profile vulnerabilities in specific widely-used encryption libraries. But POODLE is different&mdash;it\'s a flaw in the protocol itself. SSLv3 was released in 1996, and should be considered obsolete and unsafe. TLSv1, the successor to SSLv3, was released in 1999&mdash;15 years ago. Newer versions of TLS are preferable, but TLSv1 provides an acceptable, safe baseline.</p>\n\n<p>Unfortunately, disabling SSLv3 may cause compatibility problems for a very small amount of traffic on the Internet&mdash;well under 1%. We don\'t take this lightly: breaking compatibility is always a serious concern. In this case though, leaving SSLv3 enabled would risk exposing our users to eavesdropping by malicious actors, and we\'re simply unwilling to take that risk.</p>\n\n<p>As of Wednesday, October 15 at 20:00 UTC, SSLv3 was disabled for all API and SMTP traffic received by Mandrill. SSLv3 for webhooks was disabled on Thursday, October 16 at 17:00 UTC. We\'re evaluating the impact of disabling SSLv3 for all outbound mail that uses opportunistic encryption, and will post an update once that is complete.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"announcements\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"Five Lessons From Deploying Code at Mandrill\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:56:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/deploying-code-at-mandrill.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2014-09-12T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Chad\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Chad.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}