ata fields, the <a href=\"https://mandrillapp.com/activity\">Activity view</a> in your Mandrill account can display data about your emails and link directly to your CRM or backend database.\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:6:\"how-to\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:65;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"The Hidden Power of Search\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:56:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/the-hidden-power-of-search.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-10-24T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Josh\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Josh.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-10-24:/the-hidden-power-of-search.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1044:\"<p>In his <a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/email-as-a-service-as-a-service.html\">last post</a>, Loren showed how Tourbuzz is using Mandrill\'s search API to show customers their email history inside of the Tourbuzz application. Of course, advanced searching is not limited to the API. It\'s also available <a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/22211902-how-do-i-search-my-outbound-activity-in-mandrill\">inside the application</a>. Mandrill searches utilize <a href=\"http://lucene.apache.org/core/old_versioned_docs/versions/3_5_0/queryparsersyntax.html\">Lucene queries</a>, which means you can search by a single term, phrases (surrounded with double quotes), multiple terms (using the Boolean operators AND, OR, and NOT) and wildcards (* for multiple character wildcards and ? for single character). And by default, Mandrill searches all indexed fields, including any <a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/21786413-using-custom-message-metadata\">custom metadata</a> that you\'ve added. All that information is just one search field away.\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:6:\"how-to\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:66;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Email as a Service as a Service\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:61:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/email-as-a-service-as-a-service.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-10-15T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Loren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Loren.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-10-15:/email-as-a-service-as-a-service.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1049:\"<p>By now, you know that Mandrill provides tools for building out your email infrastructure. What you may not know, however, is that the tools can also be used to pass value down the chain to your own customers. Today we\'re going to examine how one of our customers has done just that with some of our more advanced email platform features.</p>\n\n<p>In their own words:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"<em>Mandrill\'s turnkey email platform allowed us to migrate from our internal postfix system to their ESP in a couple of days. That included development of our <strong>amazing new \"Email History\" feature which allows our customers to instantly see deliverability, opens, and clicks for every email</strong> handled by our system.</em></p>\n\n<p>\"<em>Our new email infrastructure has improved deliverability, vastly increased customer confidence in our system, and reduced support load for both us and our customers.</em>\"  -Alan Pinstein, cofounder, <a href=\"http://tourbuzz.net\">Tourbuzz.net</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Read on to learn how they did it.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:21:\"customer-integrations\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:67;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"Adding custom SMTP headers in your desktop email program\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:56:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/adding-custom-smtp-headers.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-10-11T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Kaitlin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Kaitlin.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-10-11:/adding-custom-smtp-headers.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:652:\"<p>If you use a desktop email client to create emails to be sent through Mandrill, one thing you might be missing out on is the ability to use a template or specify some custom options for the emails that you\'re sending.  Mandrill has an awesome <a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/21688056-using-smtp-headers-to-customize-your-messages\">SMTP headers API</a> so you can add all kinds of goodies to your emails, but desktop email clients don\'t generally make it simple to add these custom headers.  With a little bit of wrangling, though, you\'ll be off and running. Below I\'ll show you how you can add these for a couple of popular email programs.\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:6:\"how-to\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:68;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:35:\"Declaring War on No-Reply Addresses\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:65:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/declaring-war-on-no-reply-addresses.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-10-01T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Loren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Loren.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:75:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-10-01:/declaring-war-on-no-reply-addresses.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:990:\"<p>Imagine doing business with someone who doesn\'t listen to you. They talk to you often enough, but they aren\'t interested in anything you have to say. In fact, they can\'t hear you at all, as though they have their fingers in their ears while chanting \"la la la I can\'t hear you la la la.\" Not very professional, is it?</p>\n\n<p>Strangely enough, this happens millions of times a day! And it\'s perpetrated by some of the most sophisticated companies out there. They talk <strong>at</strong> their customers, not <strong>with</strong> them. They speak and refuse to listen. Odds are you can go to your inbox right now and witness this for yourself.</p>\n\n<p>What am I referring to, exactly? Why, \"no-reply\" email addresses, of course! And it\'s more than just rude, it\'s a big missed opportunity for the companies that abuse them, as well.</p>\n\n<p>That\'s why the Mandrill team is declaring war on this dreadful practice. Let\'s look at an example and consider the consequences in depth...</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:14:\"best-practices\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:69;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"I don&rsquo;t want to go in the cart - I feel fine.*\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:71:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/i-dont-want-to-go-in-the-cart-i-feel-fine.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-09-27T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Kaitlin\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Kaitlin.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-09-27:/i-dont-want-to-go-in-the-cart-i-feel-fine.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:764:\"<p>I just passed Ben (MailChimp\'s CEO) on the stairs. All I heard was him chanting \"blog post, blog post, blog post.\"</p>\n\n<p><em>\"When are you going to update the Mandrill blog?\" \"What are you guys working on?\" \"Is Mandrill dead?\"</em></p>\n\n<p>No, Mandrill isn\'t dead - it\'s very much alive. But, see, that <a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/starting-is-hard-to-do.html\">last blog post</a> that Chad made? It\'s sort of a hard act to follow. We\'ve been busy adding new features and beefing up functionality but few of these features seemed to warrant a full blog post. Plus, the Mandrill blog is sort of a nerd\'s blog, which means code and the command line and...well, more on that later. Time to rip off the band-aid. Here\'s a little bit of what we\'ve been up to: \";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"announcements\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:70;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:22:\"Starting is Hard To Do\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:52:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/starting-is-hard-to-do.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-05-22T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Chad\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Chad.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-05-22:/starting-is-hard-to-do.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1794:\"<p>Mandrill (our new <a href=\"http://mandrill.com\">email as a service product</a>, for those that don\'t know) has had an interesting history.  It started as an idea about two years ago, and its path of becoming a product is an example of a growing company trying to figure out how to start something new.</p>\n\n<p><strong>tl;dr</strong> As a company grows around a product, inertia from past success can kill short-run productivity on something new.  A way to get around this is to create a whole new team isolated from the core to break the inertia and force them to bet big on the new risky product.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/images/skunkworks.jpg\" alt=\"Mandrill Skunkworks\" width=\"250\" height=\"321\" align=\"right\" alt=\"Mandrill Skunkworks\"></p>\n\n<h2>Why Do Startups Win?</h2>\n\n<p>To a naive observer, it seems insane that tiny companies bootstrapped with no money and made up of a bunch of friends from college could ever build products that rival the output of huge companies.  The huge companies have easy access to large amounts of money.  They have built-in pools of trained experts that they\'ve hired over the years and can afford to pay well.  They have a brand that people recognize.  They have man-millenia of experience building products and systems with a proven track record of success. (they\'re big for a reason, right?)  Tiny companies have none of these things.</p>\n\n<p>So why aren\'t big companies exploding with innovative new products?  Why do they pay huge premiums to acquire tiny startups?  It can\'t be for the idea - everybody has ideas.  It would have to be for the team or the execution of the idea.  With all of these advantages, why does the big company need to pay a premium for that?  Why doesn\'t the big company just create new products from within?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:8:\"business\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}i:71;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"Public Beta of Mandrill SMTP Email Service\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:2:{s:4:\"href\";s:72:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/public-beta-of-mandrill-smtp-email-service.html\";s:3:\"rel\";s:9:\"alternate\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"updated\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"2012-04-01T00:00:00Z\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:6:\"author\";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";s:5:\"child\";a:1:{s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Chad\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:3:\"uri\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"http://blog.mandrill.com/author/Chad.html\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}s:2:\"id\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"tag:blog.mandrill.com,2012-04-01:/public-beta-of-mandrill-smtp-email-service.html/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:7:\"summary\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1707:\"<p><img src=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/images/mandrill-shield.png\" align=\"right\" height=\"262\" width=\"200\">\nAbout a year ago, we launched <a href=\"http://blog.mailchimp.com/mailchimp-launches-transactional-email-service-on-top-of-amazon-ses/\" title=\"MailChimp Launches Simple Transactional Service on Top of Amazon SES\">STS</a> - a transactional email service built on top of <a href=\"http://aws.amazon.com/ses/\">Amazon SES</a>. In that time, we\'ve seen the integration grow to a moderate success, now sending on average over 100,000 messages every day. While we\'re happy with the cool things people have built on top of our integration, we\'ve received a ton of requests from customers for features that we felt we really couldn\'t accomplish on top of a limited platform like Amazon\'s. We\'ve also spent years building a world-class platform for <a href=\"http://mailchimp.com/features/email-delivery/\">email delivery</a> and analytics, so the devs were constantly saying \"why don\'t we use this platform to build an email service that\'s MailChimp through-and-through?\" That thought turned into a prototype labs project called Mandrill which <a href=\"http://blog.mailchimp.com/the-email-person-at-amazon-web-services-is-really-really-excited/\">we are excited</a> to announce has graduated to public beta.</p>\n\n<p>At its core, Mandrill is similar in functionality to our STS integration, but using the same optimized delivery engine that MailChimp uses for the delivery of our bulk newsletters - slightly modified for one-to-one email. You still need to be a programmy nerd to use it, so if you\'re not comfortable with code and APIs, you\'ll need to find someone who is before you get started using Mandrill.</p>\n\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"html\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:4:\"term\";s:13:\"announcements\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:2:\"en\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:512;s:7:\"headers\";a:9:{s:10:\"x-amz-id-2\";s:76:\"0DiOh79lqkPc9KAdFEs0fO/4xLRAWtcuWyD4MhwdzHTBym7m6428aYyOJLJCFHSvdl2Q8CtVq+U=\";s:16:\"x-amz-request-id\";s:16:\"A697E992950AA00C\";s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Fri, 11 Sep 2015 13:22:53 GMT\";s:13:\"last-modified\";s:29:\"Tue, 04 Aug 2015 11:01:57 GMT\";s:4:\"etag\";s:34:\"\"cc45b898ef703e00306ffb91f5bad16d\"\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:15:\"application/xml\";s:14:\"content-length\";s:6:\"119624\";s:10:\"connection\";s:10:\"keep-alive\";s:6:\"server\";s:8:\"AmazonS3\";}s:5:\"build\";s:14:\"20150811143504\";}','no'),(1141,'_